Flames shot out of Thassalin's throat as the giant Thraki set a particular forest section under control and then circled above it to recognize movements. Strangely, the eerie screeching behind him quieted as he slowed down. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his back.
“What’s this, Tenuk, you’ve turned into a Thraki before!”
“If I fly myself, it’s completely different than being suddenly lifted up by a gigantic pink dragon!”
“It wasn’t that bad, was it, Kayel?”
Kayel clearly did not share Nyssis’s opinion. He looked less black than usual and his claws had dug so deeply into Thassalin’s back that the Thraki was bleeding. But Thassalin seemed unaffected by this. Still, he realized that he had scared his new friends and landed on a clearing.
“I AM SORRY, BUT I SMELLED SOMETHING. I HAD TO TAKE CARE OF IT!”
“But did you have to drag us along too?” snarled Tenuk as he climbed down from Thassalin’s back and slid down onto its tail. “And we left Retvik behind! We abandoned our large, strong warrior! How will he ever catch up with us?”
“He’ll figure something out…,” growled Nyssi. “Retvik isn’t the fastest, but he’s not dumb.”
“True, but can Retvik fly?”
Nyssi winked and turned back to Tenuk. “Of course he can fly.”
“Have you ever seen Retvik drive a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I haven't seen him drive that fancy little car Kayel owns either. Besides, he only started using the car for work because you always drove us around. He only rides his bicycle.”
Laughter echoed. It seemed suddenly very funny to Thassalin, but no one knew what he was laughing at. It took a bit too long for Thassalin to calm down.
“I'M SORRY BUT I TOOK YOUR LARGEST FRIEND IN ARMOR ON SUCH A TINY BICYCLE FOR TEMTHAN CHILDREN. IT WAS HILARIOUS! I WISH I HAD SOME KIND OF TELEPATHY. A FANTASTIC IDEA! ONE I CAN'T SHARE!”
Kayel chuckled, knowing what was going on in Thassalin's head. “Yes, I get that. But what did you smell, and why did you suddenly take off?”
Thassalin growled, lifted off, and disappeared. When he returned shortly thereafter, he threw something lifeless at Nyssi's feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare, golden-white dragon offspring. But it lacked a head. “ANOTHER DEAD ONE. I HEAR THEIR CRIES. SMELL THEIR BLOOD. SOMETHING PRESSES ME TO PROTECT AND CHASE. AS YISINI ORDERS. THEY ARE VERY NEAR.”
The powerful Thraki suddenly froze. Nyssi and Kayel also froze, looking attentively at a gap in the clearing. Something large and black stared at them and growled. Whatever it was, it spread two enormous wings and shot towards Thassalin, ignoring the three smaller beings between them. Kayel and Tenuk could just manage to take cover, but Nyssi was dragged along and almost thrown onto Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to this attack by snatching Nyssi and throwing him onto his back with his incredibly long and nimble tail before lifting himself into the air. The black, double-winged creature followed them at high speed.
Kayel annoyanceedly clicked, while he took his rifle off his back and opened a bag containing a ammunition belt. He hung the belt around his chest, but quickly realized that Nyssi, the Thraki, and the monster were out of sight.
“Hey, Tenuk, could you transform into something that can fly?” asked Kayel.
“Do you want to chase them?”
“Yes, of course!”
“But... one of them is a huge monster!”
“And so? I'm standing here with a high-quality gun in my hand and could start shooting immediately. But, well, how should I put it – I would have to see it to hit it.”
Tenuk hesitated, then stepped back to have more space. With a soft, painful grunting sound, Tenuk's body stretched, his fur turned into scales, and his arms into wings. He quickly transformed into a normal, light-blue Thraki, but his eyes remained red.
“Get on.”
Like a normally appearing Thraki, Tenuk now had a proper scaled shield running along his back. Luckily, he also grew a pair of spines on his back where Kayel could hold on. It took Tenuk a bit too long to get airborne, but once in the air, he quickly oriented himself and tried to take up the pursuit.
Tenuk and Kayel soon realized they were not alone. A second dark creature shot up beneath them, and Tenuk only just managed to avoid a collision.
"Is this the other terrifying giant monster that Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel furrowed his brow. He tried to shoot at the second beast but missed and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk did not respond. He was too focused on getting them airborne toward Nyssi and Thassalin, despite the other beast following them. Kayel awkwardly turned around to keep the monster in sight. The fact that it was pursuing them was advantageous for Kayel because it allowed him to aim and fire more easily. Two shots went through the upper wings of the beast, which howled in pain and fell back among the trees. Kayel wasn't certain if it was still pursuing them, but it certainly wouldn't be able to keep up with them.
A good distance ahead, Nyssi clung desperately while Thassalin swung around and spat flames at the blackened monster. The creature was clearly injured. It seemed furious but not ready to give up. The fireballs didn't seem to have the desired effect. As Thassalin stretched out, Nyssi seized the opportunity to draw her own weapon, an old shotgun. Though not ideal, perhaps the buckshot would deter the black beast.
